      <h1 class="text-4xl text-[#ff5a44] md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">My Journey How to Code</h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-[#6244b3]">
        Learning code – here’s my personal story and what brought me into coding.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Story -->
   
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-12 leading-relaxed">
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
  My transition into the tech industry began with a strong desire to build solutions and grow professionally. After leaving my previous job, I committed to learning web development through self-study and hands-on practice. I quickly realized that knowing how to search for answers, ask questions, and explore different tools was just as important as writing code. The following is a breakdown of how I use ChatGPT, Google, and Stack Overflow as essential parts of my learning workflow.
</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">Workflow with ChatGPT + Google + Stack Overflow</h2>

    <div class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl text-[#6244b3] font-semibold mb-2">1. ChatGPT — for fast guidance, learning, and code generation</h3>
      <p class="mb-2 font-semibold">Use cases:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 mb-4">
        <li>Quick explanation of a concept</li>
        <li>Refactor help or debugging assistance</li>
        <li>Converting old code to modern style</li>
        <li>Explaining confusing error messages in simple terms</li>
        <li>Learning step-by-step how something works</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mb-2 font-semibold">Why I love it:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700">
        <li>Fast feedback</li>
        <li>Doesn’t shame for asking beginner questions</li>
        <li>Helps me learn as I go (like a mentor sitting next to me)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl text-[#6244b3] font-semibold mb-2">2. Google — for fast searching and “link jumping”</h3>
      <p class="mb-2 font-semibold">Use cases:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 mb-4">
        <li>Searching specific error messages (e.g., <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1">ReferenceError: x is not defined site:stackoverflow.com</code>)</li>
        <li>Finding exact docs (e.g., <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1">array reduce site:developer.mozilla.org</code>)</li>
        <li>Searching GitHub issues or blogs about weird bugs</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mb-2 font-semibold">Why I love it:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700">
        <li>Super flexible, fast results</li>
        <li>You can choose the best link (docs, blog, GitHub, Stack Overflow, etc.)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl text-[#6244b3] font-semibold mb-2">3. Stack Overflow — for deep errors and proven answers</h3>
      <p class="mb-2 font-semibold">Use cases:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 mb-4">
        <li>Solving niche errors others have already faced</li>
        <li>Finding a reliable “battle-tested” solution</li>
        <li>Reading what didn’t work for others — and why</li>
        <li>Upvoted answers help avoid trial-and-error</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mb-2 font-semibold">Why I love it:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700">
        <li>Answers often include context, links, and alternatives</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Summary Section -->
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4">Summary</h3>
    <div class="grid gap-3 text-gray-700">
      <p><strong>ChatGPT:</strong> Learning, generating code, debugging help</p>
      <p><strong>Google:</strong> Searching docs, quick answers, comparison</p>
      <p><strong>Stack Overflow:</strong> Deep error solving, real-world Q&A</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Tech Learning Section -->
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4">Learning Technology</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">
      I’m a new developer, and I understand that making mistakes—like writing messy code structures, conflicting CSS classes, or incorrect logic—is a normal part of the learning process. I’m not afraid to make those mistakes because each one teaches me something valuable. What matters most is that I keep going, and every time I learn something new, I go back to fix and improve what I’ve built. Step by step, I’m becoming more confident and better at writing clean, working code.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700">
      I started by learning HTML, CSS, and JavaScript on my own. I truly love learning to code from the fundamentals—when 
      I first got curious about JavaScript, I asked AI questions like “What is JavaScript?” and “What can JavaScript do?”, 
      and from there, AI helped me list project ideas and guided me like a mentor as I started building.
      Now I’m building projects, exploring Node.js, and working toward becoming a full-time developer.
    </p>
  </section>

